{"key":"processedPost-16467817","value":{"id":16467817,"first":16465723,"last":16468165,"when":1341199329,"utime":"07/02/12 06:22 AM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>Dr. Steve Brule said:</strong><br />I've never had a problem with lids sticking, and keeping them the correct way (rubber down) makes a better seal. Leaving the foil on after sterilization will do the complete opposite of that, it'll keep the moisture out. Micropore tape is pretty much unnecessary, too.</blockquote><br />Three wrongs don't make a right.<br />Use lids rubber side up&nbsp; because they're easier to get off.&nbsp; It's somewhat strange to be concerned about the seal of a lid with four open holes.<br />Remove foil after sterilization.&nbsp; Leaving it in place causes the verm filter to become damp with moisture from the rice flour/verm below.<br />Micropore tape has saved many grows.&nbsp; I have a nice sterile lab so don't need it, but most guys here don't and as any hot surface cools, it contracts which draws in air.&nbsp; Anything which gives an extra layer of protection during cool-down is desired.<br />To the original poster, order spores from a reputable source.<br />RR"}}